firm, spurning a lower offer from rival fabric makerWest Point-Pepperell Inc.   In the continuing takeover battle for the textile giant, OdysseyPartners was offering $68.50 a share in cash for Stevens'outstanding shares under a tender offer due to expire April 22.   Stevens fell 50 cents a share to close at $67.62{ Friday in NewYork Stock Exchange composite trading.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smithreceived at least $2.2 million for 1987 in salary, exercised stockoptions and stock grants, the nation's largest automaker reportedin its proxy statement.   Smith received $867,000 in salary, earned $513,121 exercisingstock options and was awarded a stock bonus worth $800,000 when itwas granted on Dec. 7, according to the document released Friday.The stock, issued more than three years ago, is worth considerablymore now.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices pulled out of Thursday's steep slide with an unevenshowing Friday marked by strength in some blue-chip issues.   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 101.46 on Thursdayfor its fifth largest point loss ever, rose 8.29 to 2,013.93. Itfinished the week with a net loss of 76.26 points.   Bond prices tumbled and interest rates jumped for the secondconsecutive session. The dollar closed mixed, while gold pricesincreased.   On other markets, oil futures advanced for the fifth straightday.</TEXT></DOC>